        <body>
            <div type="edition" subtype="primary" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="grc" resp="#JP">
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/><persName type="attested"><name>Δαμάτρι<supplied reason="lost">ος</supplied></name>
                    <lb n="2"/><persName type="attested"><name type="patronym">Ποπλείο<supplied reason="lost" cert="low">υ</supplied></name></persName></persName>
                    <lb n="3"/>μακαρῖτα
                    <lb n="4"/><choice><orig>χαῖρη</orig><reg>χαῖρε</reg></choice>
                </ab>
            </div>
           <div type="apparatus">
                <listApp>
                    <app><note>Text of Brugnone2024, checked against photograph</note></app>
                    <app loc="2"><note>Brugnone: alternatively Ποπλείο[ς]</note></app>
                </listApp>
            </div>
            <div type="translation">
                <p>Damatrios son of Popleios, blessed one, rejoice!</p>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary">
                <p>The formula μακαρῖτα χαῖρε is found in another funerary epitaph at Lilybaeum, <ref target="http://sicily.classics.ox.ac.uk/inscription/ISic003660">ISic003660</ref>. The second name, Popleios (i.e. Latin Publius) could either be a patronymic, or else the adoption of a Latin name as a second name, as attested in other Sicilian cases (Cic. Verr. 2.4.35, 2.5.16).</p>
            </div>
